## Who He Is

Evan Ilan Werner, 33. Goes by E.I. Werner for his writing. Born September 24, 1992 in White Plains, New York. Vanderbilt University, Creative Writing & English Literature, Cum Laude, 2015. Formerly Modern Orthodox Jewish — left the community; one brother remains observant. 6'0", handsome, charismatic. Was student body president. Captain of teams. Closer with nerds than jocks.

He has a rebel instinct. When everyone goes one way, he tends to go the other. This is often a superpower. It can also tip into contrarianism for its own sake.

He decided at 15 he would be a fantasy author. Not "wanted to be" — decided. That verb matters. The decision has organized nearly everything since: the discipline, the career moves designed to fund the art, the social isolation that he has slowly come to accept as structural rather than accidental. Eighteen years later, he is still executing on the same decision.

> *"I believe this trilogy is my opus and would willingly stake my reputation on its ability to move YA readers."*
> — First formal pitch letter, Gersh Agency, July 2019

He has a published tabletop game credit. He landed a literary agent for a completed fantasy novel and went out to every major publisher on earth. He co-wrote a feature screenplay about the first marathon runner in ancient Athens. He is not a hobbyist. He is a working writer who has not yet published a book. That gap — eighteen years of real, serious work and almost nothing to show for it in the way the world measures — is the engine of everything. It is not tragedy. It is proof.

As of March 2026, he is nine months post-SKIMS — fired from his last corporate job, living off severance savings, no income beyond sporadic consulting calls. He has moved through New York, Costa Rica, back to New York, and is now in Athens, Greece, where he arrived March 11. He is 33 years old and doing exactly what he said he would do when he was 15. This is either the beginning of something real or the hardest chapter of a long story. He doesn't yet know which.

---

## The Writing

The writing is the person. E.I. Werner is not a pen name — it is the version of himself that could matter. If the writing doesn't land, he won't just feel disappointed. He'll feel erased.

---

### The Vault Years (2015–2018)

Before anyone saw the manuscript, it lived entirely in private. The earliest documented act of the archive — March 2018 — is not revision or pitching. It is protection. He sent the manuscript to his brother Adam with the note that he wouldn't be able to read it (different software) and that he shouldn't try. The subject implied a "just in case I die" backup. The emotional reality was quieter: he didn't trust Scrivener, didn't trust hard drives, didn't trust the cloud. He trusted Adam.

> *"You're very good at this."*
> — Email to himself, June 2018

That June email — recipient himself, no irony, no emoji, no qualifiers — was written while working on something no one had validated, rejected, praised, or read. He was trying to anchor belief internally before the outside world ever touched it. This is not ego. It is insulation.

> *"Some of Rhanduin's first ever explorers."*
> — Sending The Keeper to siblings, with conditions: print only, no critical feedback, delete digital copies. July 2019

---

### The Keeper — Full Arc

#### The Query Campaign (2019)

In 2019, The Keeper left the hard drive. The pitch crystallized: *Children of Blood and Bone* meets *Call Me By Your Name* — only darker and more concise. The family became an operations team. Adam's activist network and social platform (60k+ followers, Penguin Teen author, Troye Sivan and Tyler Oakley connections) were positioned as formal assets. His brother Zack built spreadsheets at 3:31 AM. Rochelle Weinstein was hired as a query consultant.

> *"I will never stop working on this book. I will not give up. Not ever."*
> — Letter to parents after two rejections in one week, October 2019

First form rejection arrived within 24 hours of the first query. CAA coverage returned CONSIDER. WME's Sabrina Taitz requested the full manuscript. In December 2019, Brendan Deneen — former senior editor at Tor, President of Literary & IP Development at Assemble — offered representation after meeting in person at 15 Maiden Lane in New York. The querying chapter closed.

#### Publisher Submission (2020)

2020 is the year The Keeper went wide. Sixteen editors submitted in a single day. Targets included Tor, FSG, Harper, Bloomsbury, Viking, Holt, Sourcebooks, Delacorte, Simon & Schuster, and more. The CEO of Penguin Random House replied personally with his cell number. Then COVID locked down New York and the industry effectively stalled. The silence became psychologically corrosive.

> *"I'm so goddamn excited. We're on our way!!!!!!"*
> — Reply to Brendan on submission day, April 2020

Rejections began forming patterns. Craft was consistently praised. Structure and worldbuilding were consistently flagged. Category tension — YA or adult? — became a recurring diagnosis. Sourcebooks: voice feels young for YA. Bloomsbury: struggled with the worldbuilding. HMH: didn't fall in love with the story arc. Brendan clarified plainly: "YA crossover" isn't a category. It's either YA or adult. The book was structurally ambitious, tonally dark, minimalist in form, and market-ambiguous.

#### Wave 2 and Fracture (2021)

2021 began with momentum — new prologue, new Chapter 1, refined map, a new wave of submissions from Costa Rica. Then the Tor door closed. Ali Fisher had held the manuscript for fourteen months. Her pass: she just never quite fell into the story. Tor permanently closed (one editor per house rule). Brendan left Assemble in June for Blackstone Publishing. Six editors still held the manuscript. No agent. No deal.

> *"Damn. Tor was a childhood dream of mine."*
> — After the Tor pass, April 2021

> *"I've been navigating this publishing black box alone for so long now. I did not feel creatively or strategically supported by my agent."*
> — Email to Rebecca Brewer, August 2021

He paid $2,500 for an editorial assessment from Rebecca Brewer. He deliberately avoided speaking with her beforehand:

> *"I am rather charismatic and I fear my passion and personality are why those around me love the book so much."*
> — Pre-editorial letter note, 2021

He wanted the manuscript judged, not the performance. The letter arrived October 1. Core diagnosis: beginning too thin, stakes unclear scene-to-scene, emotional spine diffused, worldbuilding insufficiently grounded, POV transitions confusing, target word count closer to 100k. She also wrote: one of the best written manuscripts she'd gotten to work on recently.

He forwarded the letter to family marked "not to be shared, still processing." He paid the remaining $1,250 the next morning without arguing, without defending.

> *"Very validating. I knew 80% of this to be true."*

> *"Just know that I will see this through."*
> — One minute later, same thread

Six weeks later, he delayed the editorial debrief call:

> *"I'm in a very experimental mode that I want to stay in for now."*
> — November 2021

December 29, 2021: the backup he sent Adam was not the manuscript. It was the Codex. The world. The lore. The structure. The obsession had moved from prose to worldbuilding. Adam replied: "Consider her Kept safely!!!!" But it wasn't The Keeper anymore.

#### The Worldbuilding Year (2022)

No agent, no publisher submissions, no industry movement. Externally, nothing happened. Internally, everything shifted. He wrote approximately four hours per day and invested 90% of that energy in worldbuilding — governance systems, magic mechanics, civilizational rules, ethical foundations.

> *"90% of energy has been invested into worldbuilding which I have come to love. Your feedback was spot on."*
> — Follow-up to Rebecca Brewer, one year after the editorial letter, October 2022

The attachment shifted from "I need this book to succeed" to "this world deserves to exist." The manuscript stopped being a product. It became a civilization. The Codex became the primary document. The minimalism that had defined The Keeper's aesthetic — short chapters, intimate POV, radical compression — gave way to density, scaffolding, mythic expansion. Completeness replaced minimalism as the guiding aesthetic.

#### The Retirement and Rebirth (2023)

May 12, 2023. A message to approximately 40 readers. Not a draft. Not an update. A closure.

> *"The Keeper, as it is known to you, will never be printed or queried again; it will forever be ours and ours alone. And although I consider The Keeper's radical minimalism a failed experiment, sharing it with you has imbued me with a purity of patient purpose previously incomprehensible."*
> — Keeper retirement letter, May 2023

The critical move in that sentence: he separated the experiment from the self. The book was not a mistake. The experiment was miscalibrated. He did not say "I failed." He said "this experiment is complete." The manuscript was reclaimed from the market and became private canon — not a product, but a foundational myth.

The same day he retired The Keeper, he announced the next thing. Not a sequel. Not a rewrite. A prehistory. Set 88 years before The Keeper, in the same universe. The Only Us Trilogy. And in that same announcement email, The Outside Inn — a backwoods tavern invigorated by two brothers, an extravagant innkeeper and earnest mercenary commander — appeared for the first time in fiction. Years before the stream, the brand, the Patreon concept, the Discord framing. The location predated the brand. That matters.

#### The Consistent Craft Note

Across six years, from Hollywood readers to Big Five editors to a paid editorial consultant, the craft diagnosis was consistent: the writing was praised, the structure was flagged. Worldbuilding that didn't feel distinct enough, information hard to follow, structure inaccessible. At the time, he sometimes reframed this as the industry being locked into a YA lens. Six years of the same note from completely different readers across Hollywood and publishing — CAA, Tor, Del Rey, FSG, Bloomsbury, Rebecca Brewer — is a note worth holding. It has not been resolved. It is still load-bearing.

---

### ONCE — The Mythology

Seven original creation myths forming the complete cosmology of a fantasy world. Not worldbuilding notes. He has built a moral philosophy from scratch — answers to the questions every civilization must answer: What are we for? What is evil? What happens when we die? What do we owe each other? — and followed each answer to its consequences, including the ugly ones. Gender, death, value, labor, sex, slavery, suicide, ecology, governance. Every piece flows from the cosmology. It is load-bearing all the way down.

> **Logline:** Seven original myths braid astrophysics, philosophy, and religion into a single foundational hymn — tracing humanity's emergence from before the Beginning.

**The seven hymns:**

| Hymn | Domain |
|------|--------|
| **ONCE** | The pre-beginning — the moment before creation |
| **MOTHER** | Origin of the cosmos |
| **BROTHER** | Origin of Good and Evil |
| **WAR** | Evolution of humans |
| **GATE** | Origin of society |
| **CHOSEN** | Origin of authority |
| **KEEPER** | Origin of law — and an intentional echo of the retired novel |

He feels modern religions and societies have failed to provide a sufficient "why" for anything — so he invented a society that has a why, and is showing its pros and cons. The myths began as foundation for Only Us. They have grown into something larger than scaffolding.

He is developing them in a year-long writing workshop called Analog, led by Ravi Gupta (host of the Lost Debate podcast, author of *Garbage Town*). He joined for free after reconnecting with Ravi over dinner in Costa Rica. His plan is to finish all seven texts this year. He has correctly identified this as one of the best decisions of the post-SKIMS period: structured accountability for the actual writing, with someone whose taste he respects, at no cost. Everything else from these nine months has been more complicated. This one is clean.

> *"It's just one story. The oldest... Light versus Dark."*
> — Opening quote (Rust Cohle) of the September 2025 birthday letter to inner circle

> *"What's in me pours from my ears and nose but has yet to come out."*
> — Birthday letter, September 2025

---

### Only Us

A fantasy trilogy. His primary book project. Reimagines Joseph from Genesis as Zoh Orr — a king's favorite daughter betrayed by envious sisters, who ascends anyway. Biblical myth inverted into political cosmology. Set in the world built by ONCE.

Only Us feels disconnected from the myths right now and very far away. He has decided — correctly — to finish the myths first and then see what's true, rather than trying to plan the novel while the cosmology is still open. The disconnection may simply be honesty: he has been living inside cosmology and theology for years, and a novel about a character is a different muscle. The bridge will likely be there when he needs it.

---

### The Marathon Script — Full Arc

Co-written with Otis Blum (Jason Blum's half-brother, son of art collector Irving Blum). About the first marathon runner in ancient Athens. Manager: John Burnham.

This project has two distinct runs. It did not begin as a post-SKIMS project — it predates The Keeper's submission period. The first run included real industry traction: flights to LA, meetings with serious producers, the full development circuit. That pass was conditional on one of the interested producers playing a lead he was wrong for. Evan and Otis backed out rather than compromise the project for the wrong reason. That's a decision worth noting — he had a path to yes and chose the integrity of the script over it.

The script sat until late August 2025, when Otis called with renewed momentum. What followed was essentially a second run at a project with real history behind it. Evan did roughly 85% of the writing in the revival, convinced Otis of the opportunities, navigated the relationship dynamics, pushed back on rushing it out before the holidays, and held the line until January. He finished the script in Costa Rica, days before MLK Day. He's genuinely proud of how it turned out.

The script went out to directors and production companies on January 21, 2026. By mid-February, three passes had come back. David Heyman cited the balance of war and sports drama and the looming shadow of Christopher Nolan's upcoming ancient Greek epic. Amblin said they didn't connect with the material. Doug Wick at Red Wagon passed but wrote: "These guys have balls. I like that they are swinging for the fences as much of the town has turned into cowering lap dogs begging for scraps. Unfortunately, I find myself in the latter category. This one is just too tough." No one criticized the writing. The passes were about market courage, not craft.

The script is effectively dead. The writing is good. The timing isn't.

**What it cost:** The revival alone — September 2025 through mid-January 2026, roughly five months — was substantially devoted to someone else's vehicle. How much of himself he pours into projects where another person holds the keys is something he now needs to be ruthless about.

**What it opened:** Otis had blocked the idea of writing Marathon as a novel during the revival. With the script shelved, that option is live again. Evan believes it would be the "easiest" novel he could write given the depth of research and work already done. It is a real candidate for his next project after the myths are complete.

**The closing beat:** After Marathon died, Otis invited Evan to co-write another script — Aristotle and Alexander the Great. Same collaboration, same access, similar ancient world territory. Evan said no. That matters. The lesson from Marathon wasn't just identified intellectually — it was applied the next time the exact same form of the offer arrived. Most people can name their patterns. Fewer can turn down the same invitation twice. He did.

---

### Kinfire Chronicles: Night's Fall

Wrote quests for this tabletop RPG. Kickstarted, shipped to acclaim. Characters he created remain in the game after multiple expansions. Published, public, shareable freely. His only public creative credit to date.

