## What Happened at SKIMS

He arrived hungry after the YEEZY project collapsed. He built real things — systems that scaled, tools people used, processes that stuck. The work was good.

He changed his LinkedIn title to "Principal Technical Project Manager" without explicit permission during a looser org moment. When the company formalized titles, he was the only one left with an invented one and had to revert it publicly. This was premature self-authorization — trying to externalize an internal sense of earned status before it was granted. Resentment built quietly. He started keeping score. He felt owed. He pushed back on safeguards. He talked too much in meetings. He had emotional moments — raised voice, visible frustration — followed immediately by apology emails. 99% of the time he was regulated. But leadership memory is shaped by the 1%.

His manager wrote thoughtful and direct reviews, then later left the company furious at the CTO for not receiving a VP promotion. The CTO held power close and didn't invest in people's growth. Evan was never going to "win" in that system. But his blind spots were real.

He was fired for taking someone's lunch. He thought it was abandoned; it was not. It was a clean exit for an accumulated erosion of trust.

He carries shame about this sized for something much larger than what happened. The shame isn't about the lunch. It's about the gap between who he wanted to be at SKIMS and who he became by the end. There is shared blame — the culture didn't reward openness, the CTO didn't invest in people. But the pattern belongs to him too. Both things are true, and he needs to hold both.

---

## The Year Since SKIMS (June 2025 – March 2026)

Nine months. No job applications. He left SKIMS with approximately $112,000 in combined cash and crypto. As of March 2026 he has roughly $56,000 remaining — a burn rate of around $5,100 per month. He has moved through New York, two months in Nosara, Costa Rica (where he's been coming for seven years), a brief return to his parents' house in New York, and is now in Athens, where he arrived March 11, 2026.

This section exists because this period has been a crucible. It crystallized patterns that had been present for years and made them suddenly readable — to him, and to anyone paying attention.

### What He Built

He invested roughly $12,500 and enormous management energy in a lo-fi streaming brand called Outside Inn: a contracted composer, a Moroccan animator hired after fielding over 60 applicants, lo-fi music, visual animation, streaming infrastructure. He did a deep personal brand exercise in early February 2026 — and the exercise clarified that the radio station wasn't the goal. Community around his writing was. The radio became warmup and cooldown music for the writing streams. This was the right conclusion. But the brand exercise should have happened in September 2025, before the money was spent.

He co-wrote a feature screenplay, drove the majority of the creative work, held the line against rushing it out before it was ready, finished it in Costa Rica, sent it out in January, and watched it collect three passes in six weeks. He is proud of how the script turned out. He is also clear-eyed about the fact that five months substantially belonged to someone else's vehicle.

He joined a free year-long writing workshop with someone whose taste he respects. He started streaming his writing process live. He set up expert network profiles. He surfed a lot in Costa Rica and genuinely improved.

### The Carson Situation

This is the sharpest window into who he is under financial stress, and what happens when he takes external advice over his own instincts.

Carson Thatcher is a close friend of over a decade — an accomplished producer and songwriter working well below market rate as a favor on the streaming music. A business negotiation over the music deal escalated. An AI advisor told Evan to call an earlier price discussion "an estimate, not a handshake deal" and to remove an apology Evan had instinctively drafted. Evan sent the clinical email instead — a numbered-list scope correction — the morning after Carson had sent a warm, collaborative counter-proposal to a deal that was essentially already settled on a call.

Carson was hurt, not by the money but by the tone. He said so directly: "It wasn't about the money, it was about the way in which you switched it up and about your follow up email and ultimately respect."

Evan's recovery was genuine. He took full ownership over multiple texts, put the friendship first, and made no excuses. Carson accepted it. The friendship survived. The ongoing formal business partnership did not — Carson is finishing some tracks as a kindness, but doesn't want to continue in a structured arrangement.

The lesson that crystallized from this: his relational instincts are consistently better than any strategic advice he can receive, including from AI. Under financial stress, he switches to clinical efficiency when the moment calls for warmth. His gut was right at every turn — the apology he nearly didn't send, the warmth the strategy memo told him to cut. When his instincts say lead with warmth, he should lead with warmth. Nothing overrides this.

### What the Year Revealed About His Patterns

Every major directional call during this period was correct: the writing workshop, the community focus, the streaming pivot away from a standalone radio, holding the line on the Marathon script until January, and saying no to Otis's next script invitation after Marathon died. Where he stumbled was consistently in the how — building infrastructure before validating the premise, going clinical under financial pressure, spending five months on a revival of someone else's vehicle.

The build-before-validate pattern is now extremely concrete: $12,500 and months of management time invested in a radio station before having a single viewer. The brand clarity that should have preceded the spend came months after it. He recognizes this. The fix is one question asked before any significant investment: *what is the cheapest, fastest way to test whether this works before making it beautiful?*

### Where He Is Now

He is in Athens. He has roughly $56,000 in runway. The writing workshop is real and structured. The stream is live. He is 33, mostly alone, in a foreign country, building something that has no external validation yet. He arrived with jetlag, got his gym set up and cooked his own breakfast on March 13, and streamed for the first time from Athens on March 12. Technical issues — the game crashed — but he felt more comfortable on camera than the New York streams, even though practically no one showed up.

The hard checkpoint is September 1, 2026 — evaluate whether the creative work is generating meaningful recurring revenue. December 31, 2026 is where, if the target isn't met, he looks for remote tech work. He is tracking finances with actual numbers now. That is new.

