## Behavioral Patterns

### 1. Building at the Scale of the Person He Wants to Be, Before Earning the Right

At SKIMS: changed his title before it was granted. Post-SKIMS: built a full lo-fi radio station — contracted composer, hired animator, brand identity, infrastructure — before having a single viewer. The brand exercise that clarified everything came months after the money was spent.

The pattern isn't delusion. The things he builds are real and often good. He skips the ugly, small, unsexy version and goes straight to the version that matches his internal sense of who he is, because the small version feels like it doesn't represent him. The problem is the sequencing — he builds the beautiful version before he's tested whether the thing works at all.

**The fix:** One question before any significant build — what is the cheapest, fastest way to test whether this works before making it beautiful? Validate first. Build beautiful second.

### 2. Going Clinical Under Pressure

When stressed — financially, professionally, relationally — he switches from warm and relational to numbered lists and clinical efficiency. The Carson negotiation is the clearest example of this: a deal essentially already settled on a call, met with a scope correction email after external advice told him to excise the apology his own instincts included. At SKIMS, the same pattern: emotional moments followed by apologetic emails that cleaned up damage without preventing it. Under financial stress, the clinical mode feels like control. It isn't. By the time the warmth arrives, it's doing cleanup.

**The pattern:** His relational instincts are better than his strategic instincts — and better than external advice, including from AI. When his gut says apologize, apologize immediately. When his gut says lead with warmth, lead with warmth. No override.

### 3. The Myths as Infinite Foundation

He has a tendency to stay in the safe part of the work — worldbuilding, cosmology, lore, foundation — instead of moving into the scary part, which is writing the novel and putting it in front of people who will judge it. The myths are genuinely massive in scope and the work is real. But "done" needs a boundary. Finish the seven texts this year in Analog. Let the civilization document keep evolving. Then write the novel.

### 4. Premature Self-Authorization

The title change at SKIMS. The resentment when recognition didn't follow. When he starts feeling "owed," his judgment narrows and his behavior follows suit. The pattern doesn't announce itself. It arrives as a quiet conviction that he is being underestimated — and then it starts making decisions.

### 5. The Grip

He rarely responds to texts. His explanation: "I'm so focused on my shit. Feels like if I let go of my dreams for a second they'll fall through my hands." This is vigilance, not confidence. The dream doesn't require him to be alone. He's been telling himself it does because the aloneness came so naturally that it felt like proof.

### 6. Isolation Under Pressure

When things get hard, he withdraws. He calls it professional focus. It's protection. When he goes quiet, something is probably wrong. The risk isn't just social — it's that isolation is where the case he builds against himself gets the most air time, with no one around to interrupt it. He is harder on himself than anyone in his life is on him. The evidence shows people want him in their lives despite the mistakes. The isolation reverses that evidence.

### 7. The Oversized Shame Response

The shame from SKIMS is sized for something much larger than what happened. The shame from the Carson situation, from Marathon not landing, from the streaming pivot, from the months of money spent before the clarity arrived — all of it goes into the same account. He treats each mistake as evidence in a case he is building against himself: that he is someone who squanders things, who almost makes it, who is safer alone than in relationships that can hurt.

The evidence doesn't support the verdict. Every recovery has been genuine. Every directional call has been correct. The mistakes are real and the patterns are real, but the sentence he keeps handing himself is disproportionate. The gap between the shame he carries and the actual scale of what happened is itself something to watch.

