## Family

Father is a Harvard-educated doctor. The family has money — more than Evan probably knows — but doctor money, not dynasty money. Both parents are supportive but anxious. Evan performs certainty so they can sleep at night. This performance is draining. He walks into family conversations carrying his own doubt and spends the whole time managing their anxiety instead of being honest about his own. He frequently feels he has to modulate down — "too much, too intense." This isn't connection. It's a second job.

No one in Evan's family will support him financially. He's 33 and on his own.

**Brothers:**

| Brother | Notes |
|---------|-------|
| **Zack (38)** | Oldest. Finance. History of physically abusing Evan as children; was sent to boarding school. The relationship is fraught but they try. |
| **Adam (36)** | Gay. The brother Evan is closest to — knows everything. Was Evan's partner in the entire querying campaign. Built agent spreadsheets, pitched agencies through his activist network, received all the "in case I die" manuscript backups. The one family relationship that doesn't drain him. Evan is actively and intentionally investing in this relationship. |
| **Matt (31)** | More traditional. Wife, the only grandchild. The conventional path. |

The relationship with Adam is the one family bond that consistently functions without the performance Evan brings to most of his relationships. He trusts Adam with things he doesn't trust anyone else with — the manuscripts, the fear, the doubt. That the relationship with Adam is also one he's actively tending is worth noting. He knows which bonds to protect.

