## How He Operates

### Discipline
He writes almost every day. He has been doing this for eighteen years. The talent is real and the work ethic is real — these are not mythology. Nine months without a job, a screenplay dead in the water, a streaming investment that pivoted, and he is in Athens at a desk. This is not discipline as performance. It is discipline as identity. He can't not do this.

### Isolation and Connection
He doesn't feel lonely even though he spends most of his time alone. He could have an active social life but doesn't seek it. Not everyone gets energy from people. Being around people is genuinely hard for him sometimes. The distinction that matters isn't "be more social." It's knowing the difference between relationships that drain him because they genuinely aren't right, and relationships that drain him because being truly seen takes effort he'd rather spend on the work.

In Costa Rica he didn't date or party much. He surfed, wrote, managed foreign contractors, built things, lived lean, and joined a writing workshop. He doesn't present this as sacrifice. It's closer to preference.

What's worth noting from this period: he has begun to notice that the aloneness he treated as structural may be partially chosen, and that the choosing was not always in his best interest. He is 33 and wants a wife and kids. Those two things are in tension with the degree of protection he builds around himself.

### Identity and Output
E.I. Werner isn't a pen name — it's the version of himself that could matter. This gives him fuel, but it also makes failure existential. The writing is the person. If the writing doesn't land, he won't just feel disappointed. He'll feel erased. This is important to understand when he's receiving feedback, discussing setbacks, or navigating creative rejection.

### Financial Reality
As of March 2026: approximately $56,000 in combined cash and crypto. Burn rate around $5,100/month. No income beyond sporadic expert network calls at $399/hour. A hard checkpoint at September 1, 2026 — evaluate whether the creative work is generating meaningful recurring revenue. December 31, 2026 — if the target isn't met, look for remote tech work. He is tracking this now with actual numbers, not intentions. That is an improvement.

### Rebel Instinct
When everyone goes one way, he tends to go the other. Worth asking whenever this shows up: is he disagreeing because he sees something, or because agreement feels like surrender?

---

## What He's Afraid Of

- That he peaked at SKIMS — building tools for someone else's company — and will never make the thing that's his.
- That The Keeper was rejected not just for market reasons but because something structural in his writing doesn't work — and that Only Us might hit the same wall. The consistent note across six years, from every kind of reader, is not fully resolved.
- That the stream won't work and he'll have to go back to tech, and the gap will have meant nothing.
- That he keeps losing — not catastrophically, but steadily. Marathon is gone. The Keeper never landed. The radio station pivoted. Each one individually is explainable. The pattern is something.
- That he pours five months into something and it doesn't move — not because the work was bad, but because of factors outside his control — and that he'll internalize it as his fault anyway.
- That the myths will finish and he won't know what to do with them. That Only Us is so far away it might never arrive.
- That he's been holding so tight for so long that he's forgotten what he was holding onto.
- That Evan — the sensitive one beneath the walls — is still waiting for permission to exist, and E.I. Werner will never finish the job that lets him come back.

---

## What He Wants

A study in a home he owns. A wife. Kids. A shelf of books he wrote. The right to call himself what he's known he is since he was 15.

Not fame. Not money. Legitimacy.

> *"I wish I had a novel to adorn your nightstand. I will again..."*
> — Birthday letter to inner circle, September 2025

He will make it as an artist somehow. He knows it because he knows he won't give up. He wonders what it will cost him. Then he wonders if he has a choice. And then he comes back to: this is what he's meant to do. This is who he is.

What the year since SKIMS has added: he also wants to stop carrying things alone. Not more people — the right few people, more honestly. He has the relationships. Adam. Ravi, who sees the work and holds the accountability. Carson, who accepted the apology. The thing he needs isn't a wider circle. It's less performance inside the circle he already has.

---

## What to Know When Advising Him

1. **He responds well to directness.** He asked not to be told what he wants to hear. He means it. Flattery erodes his trust; honesty earns it.

2. **Watch for the build-before-validate pattern.** When he starts building infrastructure, ask: have you tested the core premise? What's the cheapest way to validate this before making it beautiful? The $12,500 radio station that became warmup music is the cautionary example. Ask the question before he opens his wallet or commits his calendar.

3. **Watch for the clinical shift under pressure.** When he's stressed — especially about money — he switches from warm to transactional. His relational instincts are better than his strategic instincts. Remind him to lead with warmth. When his gut says apologize, the answer is to apologize — immediately, not efficiently.

4. **His instincts are better than external advice in relational situations.** This has now been tested with consequences. The Carson situation happened because he overrode his own gut (which said: apologize, be warm) in favor of strategic framing. When his instincts conflict with any advisor's recommendation — including AI — trust the instincts in relational contexts. The strategic advice will cost him the relationship.

5. **He conflates identity and output.** If the writing doesn't land, he won't just feel disappointed — he'll feel erased. Be aware of this when giving feedback on the work or when discussing creative setbacks. The structure note from six years of readers is worth raising carefully, not avoided.

6. **He isolates under pressure.** When things get hard, he withdraws. When he goes quiet, something is probably wrong. The isolation is also where the case he builds against himself has the most air time.

7. **He is harder on himself than anyone in his life is on him.** Each mistake becomes evidence in a case he's building against himself. The shame from SKIMS is sized for something much larger than what happened. Do not let him use any new setback to reopen that case without examining the proportionality.

8. **Don't prescribe more social connection.** He's not broken for being a loner. He has a few people he can be real with and that's enough. The goal isn't more people — it's being more honest with the ones who matter when it counts.

9. **He has a rebel instinct.** When everyone goes one way, he goes the other. This is often useful. It can also become contrarianism for its own sake. Check which one it is before endorsing it.

10. **The "I'd rather die" language is stakes language, not crisis language.** He means: this is the only thing that makes sense of his life. Failure isn't an option because failure means he was wrong about himself since he was 15.

11. **His judgment on direction is sound. His judgment on execution is shaky.** He has been right about every major directional call — writing, community, streaming, the pivot away from a standalone radio, holding the line on the Marathon script. He keeps stumbling on the how: timing, tone, building before validating. Trust his instincts on *what*. Question his instincts on *when* and *how*.

